node.title: Rioter who took Pelosi's lectern should get 90 days in prison, feds say
node.description: A photo of Johnson carrying the podium went viral, and in texts following the insurrection he told people he "broke the internet" and was "finally famous," according to prosecutors.

node.title: Russia-Ukraine crisis will have an "impact on Americans," Rubio says

node.title: Covid-19: Advertising watchdog investigating vaccine 'risks' billboard in Auckland
node.description: The advertising watchdog is looking into a billboard using the image of a Dunedin man who died after getting a Covid-19 vaccine.

node.title: Second Moana Pasifika game postponed
node.description: Moana Pasifika's Super Rugby Pacific game against the Chiefs this weekend has been postponed because of player welfare concerns.

node.title: Watch Live: Biden updates nation as U.S. vows new Russia sanctions
node.description: President Biden is speaking as Ukraine's defense minister says Russia has "taken another step towards the revival of the Soviet Union."

node.title: Kids' mental health takes toll on parents' work, survey finds
node.description: The survey — from the child advocacy group On Our Sleeves — found that 53% of parents have missed work at least once a month to deal with their children's mental health.

node.title: Djokovic happy with his return to tennis
node.description: World number one Novak Djokovic belatedly began his 2022 campaign with a convincing defeat of Italian teenager Lorenzo Musetti at the Dubai Championships.

node.title: Video shows U.S. Coast Guard rescuing shark bite victim
node.description: A fishing boat crew called the Coast Guard after tightening a tourniquet around the man's arm "to prevent further blood loss."

node.title: "Family Reunion" actress Jaida Benjamin found safe
node.description: The 27-year-old had last been seen Saturday in Studio City, L.A. police say.

node.title: Waikato rolls out rapid antigen testing as labs reach capacity
node.description: The demand is causing a delay to process tests in the lab, with the DHB saying some tests may take up to seven days for a result.

node.title: Supreme Court rejects Trump bid to shield January 6 records
node.description: The Supreme Court already rejected Trump's emergency request to block the release of his records to the January 6 select committee.

node.title: Supreme Court to hear Colorado clash over LGBTQ rights and religious liberty
node.description: The court will decide the question of "whether applying a public-accommodation law to compel an artist to speak or stay silent violates the Free Speech Clause of the First Amendment."

node.title: Colombia to declare Pablo Escobar's "cocaine hippos" invasive species
node.description: Escobar's hippos have become a sort of local tourist attraction in the years since the kingpin was killed by police in 1993.

node.title: Verdict reached in federal hate crimes trial for killing of Ahmaud Arbery
node.description: Travis McMichael, Gregory McMichael and William "Roddie" Bryan were convicted of murder and other charges in November.

node.title: Oil prices near $100 a barrel as Ukraine crisis deepens
node.description: Mounting concerns over the conflict are hitting global financial markets driving up crude prices to an eight-year high.

node.title: Britney Spears reportedly signs $15 million book deal
node.description: Britney's sister, Jamie Lynn Spears, recently released a book of her own that led to a very public feud.

node.title: Soccer stars Rapinoe and Morgan on $24M settlement: "Equal pay from here on out"
node.description: The settlement includes backpay for previous World Cup prize money.

node.title: Troops on Ukraine's front line struggle to predict Putin's next move
node.description: A war that simmered for 8 years in eastern Ukraine has ramped up, and troops in the trenches tell CBS News they don't know what to expect next from Russia's leader.

node.title: "That is not my son!": Texas father discovers wrong body in coffin
node.description: Two bodies were incorrectly identified at several points, leading to their being switched and even the wrong one being cremated, CBS Dallas reports.

node.title: Explosion at gold mining site kills dozens: "Bodies everywhere"
node.description: The explosion was believed to have been caused by chemicals used to treat gold that were stocked at the site.

node.title: U.S. imposes sanctions after Putin recognizes breakaway Ukraine regions
node.description: White House press secretary Jen Psaki said the penalties are "separate from and would be in addition to the swift and severe economic measures" the U.S. has been preparing with allies.

node.title: Homemade rocket fuel displaces 22 students at BYU dorm
node.description: The failed DIY-experiment was a "volatile mixture" that engulfed the walls in flames, police said.

node.title: Jane "Nightbirde" Marczewski, "AGT" contestant, dies at 31
node.description: She was suffering from cancer. She'd stunned the "America's Got Talent" judges with her performance of an original song called "It's OK."

node.title: Biden has started interviewing Supreme Court candidates
node.description: The president previously said he has narrowed his list down to four choices. He is expected to announce a nominee by the end of February.

node.title: Colombia partially decriminalizes abortion
node.description: Abortion advocates say the country's ruling is a "triumph for human rights."

node.title: U.S. and allies vow new sanctions over Putin's "act of war" in Ukraine

node.title: 16-year-old chess prodigy stuns world champion Magnus Carlsen

node.title: Illinois man held on $1 million bail for alleged anti-gay attack

node.title: Tonga gets internet service back five weeks after volcanic eruption
